{"award_age":72.0,"bio_image":"full\/f353b9ae5f956300a530a7e286c23086e485bd6b.jpg","category":"Physics","country":"Germany","date_of_birth":"1928-08-25T00:00:00.000Z","date_of_death":null,"gender":"male","image_urls":["http:\/\/upload.wikimedia.org\/wikipedia\/commons\/thumb\/e\/e9\/Herbert_Kroemer.jpg\/220px-Herbert_Kroemer.jpg"],"link":"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Herbert_Kroemer","mini_bio":"<p><b>Herbert Kroemer<\/b> (born August 25, 1928), a professor of electrical and computer engineering at the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/University_of_California,_Santa_Barbara\" title=\"University of California, Santa Barbara\">University of California, Santa Barbara<\/a>, received his Ph.D. in <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Theoretical_physics\" title=\"Theoretical physics\">theoretical physics<\/a> in 1952 from the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/University_of_G%C3%B6ttingen\" title=\"University of G\u00f6ttingen\">University of G\u00f6ttingen<\/a>, Germany, with a dissertation on <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Hot_electron\" title=\"Hot electron\" class=\"mw-redirect\">hot electron<\/a> effects in the then-new <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Transistor\" title=\"Transistor\">transistor<\/a>, setting the stage for a career in research on the physics of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Semiconductor_device\" title=\"Semiconductor device\">semiconductor devices<\/a>. In 2000, Kroemer, along with <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Zhores_I._Alferov\" title=\"Zhores I. Alferov\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Zhores I. Alferov<\/a>, was awarded the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nobel_Prize_in_Physics\" title=\"Nobel Prize in Physics\">Nobel Prize in Physics<\/a> \"for developing semiconductor heterostructures used in high-speed- and opto-electronics\". The other co-recipient of the Nobel Prize was <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Jack_Kilby\" title=\"Jack Kilby\">Jack Kilby<\/a> for his invention and development of integrated circuits and micro-chips.<\/p><p>He worked in a number of research laboratories in <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Germany\" title=\"Germany\">Germany<\/a> and the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/United_States\" title=\"United States\">United States<\/a> and taught <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Electrical_engineering\" title=\"Electrical engineering\">electrical engineering<\/a> at the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/University_of_Colorado_at_Boulder\" title=\"University of Colorado at Boulder\" class=\"mw-redirect\">University of Colorado<\/a> from 1968 to 1976. He joined the UCSB faculty in 1976, focusing its semiconductor research program on the emerging compound semiconductor technology rather than on mainstream <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Silicon\" title=\"Silicon\">silicon<\/a> technology.<\/p><p>Kroemer was elected as a member of the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/National_Academy_of_Engineering\" title=\"National Academy of Engineering\">National Academy of Engineering<\/a> in 1997 and the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/United_States_National_Academy_of_Sciences\" title=\"United States National Academy of Sciences\" class=\"mw-redirect\">National Academy of Sciences<\/a> in 2003. He always preferred to work on problems that are ahead of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Mainstream\" title=\"Mainstream\">mainstream<\/a> <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Technology\" title=\"Technology\">technology<\/a>. In the 1950s, he invented the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Drift-field_transistor\" title=\"Drift-field transistor\">drift transistor<\/a> and was the first to point out that advantages could be gained in various semiconductor devices by incorporating <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Heterojunction\" title=\"Heterojunction\">heterojunctions<\/a>. Most notably, in 1963 he proposed the concept of the double-<a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Heterostructure\" title=\"Heterostructure\" class=\"mw-redirect\">heterostructure<\/a> <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Laser\" title=\"Laser\">laser<\/a>, which is now a central concept in the field of semiconductor lasers. Kroemer became an early pioneer in <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Molecular_beam_epitaxy\" title=\"Molecular beam epitaxy\">molecular beam epitaxy<\/a>, concentrating on applying the technology to untried new materials.<\/p><p>Along with <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Charles_Kittel\" title=\"Charles Kittel\">Charles Kittel<\/a> he co-authored the popular textbook <i>Thermal Physics<\/i>, first published in 1980, and still used today. He is also the author of the textbook <i>Quantum Mechanics for Engineering, Materials Science and Applied Physics<\/i>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Herbert_Kroemer#cite_note-2\"><span>[<\/span>2<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><\/p>","name":"Herbert Kroemer","place_of_birth":"Weimar ,  Germany","place_of_death":null,"text":"Herbert Kroemer , Physics, 2000","year":2000.0}